[Event "Opening Compass for Black and White"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Date "2023.08.14"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/29245287"]

1. -- { I have never really liked working on openings. That is why I was initially reluctant to create a course about the first phase of the game. Then I realized that I could make a course not just about opening lines that need memorization. I understood that I could show the principles that hide behind those moves. I could also explain the deeper reasons that make up the foundations of those principles.

The principles are quite easy and straightforward. Many players know them:

1. Fight for the center

2. Develop your pieces

3. Castle your king

However, I did not want this course to be a boring lecture about well-known facts. I wanted to show what to do and what not to do in the opening, using model examples. I was looking for examples where one player’s win was a direct result of a violation of these principles by the opponent. I checked hundreds of famous games, I checked the games that I played myself, and I checked Magnus Carlsen’s games. My goal was to find short games where one side was following the principles and the other side violated some principles.

Unfortunately I found two instructive examples where I was the one violating the principles… Anish Giri crushed me brilliantly when we played each other on the first board of the Qatar Masters back in 2014.

In my defense, I also found a few examples from the games of young Magnus, where he lost quickly due to mistakes (not blunders!) in the opening.

You will find 27 games that reveal in depth the importance of the aforementioned principles (Center+Development+Castle) . They also show how you can exploit your opponent’s lack of respect towards these principles.

At the end of the chapter dedicated to the center and castling, I show examples where blindly following the principles can be a mistake as well. You should not only follow the principles but also understand the deeper reasons behind them.

Another six games show the importance of the fourth, lesser known principle. The principles state that you need to fight for the center, develop pieces, and castle your king as quickly as possible!

The final games show examples where one of the players needed one more tempo to make things right, but never got that chance.

In this course, I took a step further. I decided to create a short opening repertoire for both colors (!) that is consistent with opening principles. This was much more challenging than I anticipated! Most openings violate at least one of the principles. It does not mean that they are bad! Not at all! It only means that they are harder to play.

I think beginners should play openings that generally follow principles. Once they become stronger and more knowledgeable, they will understand when it is justified to deviate from these principles.

Here is an example from mathematics to illustrate my point. When we teach numbers to small children, we say that there are even numbers and odd numbers. Even numbers are divisible by two, but odd numbers are not. We are saying that you cannot divide five by two because five is an odd number. Is that completely true? Of course not! Five divided by two is 2.5! The child is simply not ready to deal with fractions yet. We also say that you cannot subtract a bigger number from a smaller one. That is also not true! There are negative numbers!

As the child grows in understanding we can start teaching it about negative numbers and fractions. We can say that you can subtract any two numbers and you can divide any two numbers. Well, you still cannot divide by zero. There are more steps in mathematics at a later stage. It turns out that you can take a square root of negative numbers. The result just leaves the set of real numbers and goes to complex ones. When I continued my math study in university, I discovered that there are different kinds of infinity (that is what you get when you divide by zero) . Some infinities are more infinite than others… ---

Why am I telling you all this? Just like mathematics, chess is a very deep and complex field of study. For now, I want you to deeply understand and implement the opening principles. Just like with natural numbers, you should first feel comfortable adding and multiplying those. When you become great at doing this, the next steps will be much easier for you.

The opening repertoire that I suggest for White is centered around 1.e4. Unlike most other opening courses on Chessable, I finish the line quite early, when nothing reasonable can stop the completion of your development.

I also sometime give a few useful moves that you can consider making after your development is completed. In all the lines for the White repertoire White is either better or the position is equal.

The opening repertoire for Black was much more challenging to create. We are going to play e7-e5 or d7-d5. We will put a pawn in the center as quickly as possible.

I tried to cover all the lines that can prevent us from naturally completing our development. In the main openings, Black may get a slightly worse position, but my goal was to give you moves that you can understand. I did not want you to just memorize the moves. I selected the lines where every move you play is natural and follows the principles (with very few exceptions) .

I hope you will enjoy the course. I certainly enjoyed creating it for you! } } *

[Event "Opening Compass for Black and White"]
[White "1) Center"]
