[ECO "B00"]

1. e4 { Center! Development! Castle! As quickly as possible! These are the main things that should be going through your mind when you start any game of chess. Why is that? We will discuss every aspect in-depth separately.

A very short explanation goes something like this. To win the game, you need to use as many pieces as you can. You can beat only much-much weaker opponents with a fraction of the forces available to you. To use your pieces you need to develop them so that they start putting pressure on your opponent's position. Thus the development part is somewhat explained.

To develop your pieces freely without the danger of being harassed by pawns, you need to put your pawns in the center. Usually, it is d4+e4 (for White), and d5+e5 (for Black) squares. Although sometimes you can extend the definition of a center to include c4+f4 squares (for White), and c5+f5 squares (for Black). They act like a shield for your more valued pieces, they also are ready to kick away your opponent's more valuable pieces (like knights and bishops).

When you castle, you put your king to safety (since your central pawns left, your king no longer has any cover) and it helps you develop your rook.

And finally, you need to try to do it as quickly as possible because time is money! In this case, if you are reluctant to develop your pieces or put your king to safety quickly then your opponent will simply have more pieces in the game. You may pay a very big price for that. You will see examples of that in the following chapters. } } h6? ( { Check what could happen if Black just develops the knights without the pawns in the center. } 1...Nc6 2.d4 2...Nf6? { It was not too late to fight for the center 2...d5 $14 or 2...e5 $14 } 3.e5!? { This is a trickier try. Second-best according to Stockfish. } { The best according to Stockfish 3.d5!? Ne5 4.f4! Ng6 5.e5! Ng8 White gets all the space and Black is nowhere near developing his pieces or castling the king 6.Nf3 $16 } 3...Nd5? { 3...Ng8□ 4.Nf3 $16 } 4.c4! Nb6 5.d5! Nxe5 6.c5! Nbc4 { The strongest win is } 7.Qd4! { 7.f4+- Winning one of the knights. } 7...b5 8.cxb6+- { White is winning one of the knights. } ) 
2. d4 a6? } { Here are the main reasons for putting your pawns into the center.

1. The room behind the pawns now 'belongs' to you. You can now freely use those squares for your pieces, for example, it makes the development of your bishops easier.

2. The more you advance your central pawns the less space remains for your opponent! } 
3. Nf3 Nf6 
4. e5 } Nd5 
5. c4! { The poor knight cannot find a place to stand! } Nb6 
6. d5+- { How many squares belong to White? And how many squares are under Black's control? } *

