21. Bf4 Nhg4 
22. Kf1 Ne4 } { My opponent resigned in a hopeless position. So what happened? The start of the game was so good for White.. White could not find a plan for opening the position. It stayed closed, so Black completed the development. Also, White's control over the center was only in White's imagination due to a strong f7-f5 move. In the vast majority of cases, White has either the e4 square or the b1/h7 diagonal when the pawn is on e5. Usually, it allows the kingside attack. That was not the case here! It was hard for White to open the position or find a single target in Black's position. That is why White lost time maneuvering the knight. The fundamental mistake was also the h2-h4 move. It is a typical move for the French Defence pawn structure but not for this one! } 
