25. Qg2 Rh3!! } { White resigned just before the checkmate. Why did White lose so terribly? Well, at one point Rotlewi decided to put some pawns in the center. I want to remind you that the main fundamental reasons for putting your pawns in the center are:

1. Control the space behind the pawns. This makes development easy.

2. Leave less room for your opponent's pieces. This makes the development harder for your opponent.

None of that was true in this game! First and foremost, the minor pieces were already developed! Secondly, White did not control the square behind the f- and e-pawns! Thirdly, pushing those pawns did not restrict Black in any way because the position was open.

Another reason was that White did not complete their development! And the cherry on top of the cake for Black was that the king on g1 was not safe after the f-pawn moved! Rotlewi chose the wrong time to fight for the center! Usually, you should do that early in the opening, not in the middlegame! I like to joke that Black was playing the middlegame while White was still in the opening phase of the game:-) } ( { The game could continue } 25...Rh3 26.Qxe4 Rxh2 ) 
