{ Let us talk about development. The point of it is to bring your pieces into play. Otherwise, you will not be using the full potential of your chess army. We have already clarified that you need some control over the center to be able to develop your pieces. Now, the question is where exactly you should put them.

Here are some key ideas to bear in mind when developing your pieces. Generally speaking, a piece is well-placed if it is attacking one of the central squares. Alternatively, a piece is well-placed if it is attacking one of your opponent's pieces. In most other cases, the piece will not be active. The exception to this rule is, for example, a rook on an open file.

Let me give you a few examples. } 1. e4 } ( 1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.cxd5 cxd5 4.Nc3 Nf6 5.Bf4 Nc6 6.e3 e6 7.Bd3 Be7 8.Nf3 O-O 9.O-O Bd7 10.Rc1 $14 { White has developed the pieces into active squares. Minor pieces are controlling the center and some of them are attacking the opponent's pawns. The rook is on an open file, even though it is just 'looking' at its own knight. Black's knights are well-placed but the bishops are passive. They do not control the central squares and are not attacking anyone. } ) e6 ( 1...e5 2.Nh3? { The knight is not controlling the center and it is not attacking anything. } 2...Nf6!? { The knight is attacking the center and an opponent's piece. } 3.Nc3 Bb4 $15 { The bishop is attacking a piece. } { 3...Bc5 $15 The bishop is attacking the central square and the pawn on f2. }{ 3...Nc6 $17 The knight is controlling the center. }{ 3...Be7?! The bishop is not controlling the center and it is not attacking anything. }) 
2. d4 d5 
3. exd5 exd5 
4. Nf3 } 
5. Bd3 } { Very often when playing with Black pieces, you will not be able to put your pieces on the most active squares. For example, the pin after Bg5 could be annoying, so in this case Be7 is a sound move. } 
6. O-O O-O 
7. Re1 } { The rook goes to an open file and attacks the bishop. } c6 
8. Bg5 } ( { • } 8.Bf4 $14 ) ( { • } 8.Be3= { This is a little passive. The bishop is only defending and it is blocking the rook. } ) Nbd7 
9. Nc3 $14  } { White developed the pieces to active squares. White is slightly better but Black is solid. } *


