13. Rhd1 { White is not afraid of the pawn fork. } b5 
14. Nxe6 { Again, this is all possible due to the enormous lead in development. Here Rubinstein had to find the only move. } fxe6? { Rubinstein made only one mistake and it lead to a losing position. Why did that happen? It is much harder to play if you are behind in development so much. } ( 14...Rb8□ { That is one difficult move to consider. So many pieces are hanging, and Black has to play quiet move. } 15.Nc7+ Ke7 { 15...Kd8 16.Bxf7! bxa4 17.e5! White continues the attack on the king even without the queens. 17...Rxb2+ 18.Kf1 Bb4 18...Ke7?! 19.Be6 $16 Black is paralyzed and cannot complete the development. 19.e6 Rd2 20.exd7 $13 White restores the material balance. } 16.Nxb5!? { This would be a human way to continue the game. White is somewhat restoring the material balance. } { 16.Nd5+ Kd8 17.Nab6 bxc4 18.Nxc4= $13 Even here White has enough compensation with some accurate play. } 16...axb5 17.Bxb5 $13 { Our bishop on b5 is indirectly protected since the c8-bishop is under the attack. White will have three pawns for the piece. Black will need a few more moves to include all the pieces. In the meantime, White would transfer the knight to d5 and start pushing some pawns. } ) 
15. Bxe6! } bxa4 { Of course, White needed to see all of this before letting the b7-b5 fork. } ( { • } 15...Ne5 16.Bxc8! { It is wrong to trade your active rook for your opponent's passive one. 16.Rxc8+? Rxc8 17.Bxc8 bxa4 $13 } 16...bxa4 17.f4! { White has an overwhelming activity. } 17...Ng6 18.f5 Ne5 19.Rd5 { The central pawns together with all the pieces will crush Black. For example, } 19...Ng4 20.Bd7+ Kf7 21.h3! { 21.e5!? } Nf6 22.Be6+! Ke8 23.Rd4+- ) ( { • } 15...Nf6 16.Bxc8! { It is wrong to trade your active rook for the passive one! 16.Rxc8+? Rxc8 17.Bxc8 bxa4 $14 } 16...bxa4 17.e5! { Where does the poor knight go? When is Black going to develop the pieces? } 17...Nh5 { 17...Ng8 This is just pathetic... 18.Bd7+!? Kf7 19.Rc7 Ne7 20.f4+- } 18.Bd7+ Kf7 19.Bxa4+- ) 
16. Rxc8+! Rxc8 
17. Bxd7+! Kd8 
18. Bg4+ } Bd6 ( 18...Kc7 19.Rc1++- { Wins the whole rook. } ) 
19. Bxc8+- ( { And the rest was a matter of technique. White simply got too much extra material. } 19.Rxd6+? Kc7 $16 ) Ke7 ( 19...Kxc8 20.Rxd6+- ) 
20. Bxa6 Rb8 
21. Rb1 g5 
22. b3 h5 
23. Bd3 a3 
24. Bc4 h4 
25. h3 Rf8 
26. Rd1 Rf4 
27. f3 Rf8 
28. Rd5 Bf4 
29. Kd3 Bc1 
30. b4 Rb8 
31. Kc3 Kf6 
32. b5 { So why did Black lose? The answer is that White had more pieces in the game, the attack came naturally. Black had to find a lot of accurate moves to not lose quickly. Technically speaking, Black made only one decisive mistake. One can break these guidelines for various reasons. However - it makes the game much more difficult. In this case, Akiba Rubinstein decided to give up the development and the king's safety to acquire a long-term two-bishop advantage. It would be completely justified if he were to find all the correct moves. That is why I strongly recommend beginners and club-level players follow these guidelines first. Eventually, you will be able to expand your understanding by breaking these rules. } 1-0

