{ Here is the famous Immortal Game. } 1. e4 } e5 
2. f4 { The King's gambit was popular in those days. White is ready to sacrifice the pawn and the ability to castle just to get control over the center. } exf4 
3. Bc4 Qh4+ { White will not castle today. However, the problem with this move is that the queen will be kicked out by the Knight soon. } 
4. Kf1 b5 { No need for that. Black should have focused on developing his pieces and castling. } ( { • } 4...Nf6!? 5.Nf3 Qh6 6.Nc3 { 6.e5 d5 $17 That is one typical move in many openings. } 6...d6 7.d4 Be7 $15 { Black will castle the king and develop the remaining pieces soon. } ) ( { • } 4...d6!? 5.Nf3 Qh6 6.d4 Nf6 7.Nc3 Be7 $15 ) 
5. Bxb5 Nf6 
6. Nf3! Qh6 
7. d3 ( { • } 7.Nc3! ) ( { • } 7.d4! Nxe4 8.Qe2 $14 ) Nh5?! } { Black should have developed some pieces! Instead, Black is trying to win some material. } ( { • } 7...Bc5 $13 ) ( { • } 7...Nc6 $13 ) 
8. Nh4?! ( { • The strongest was } 8.Rg1 $14 { This move neutralizes the threat and creates the threat for White. } ) ( { • White could even afford to give up the exchange for the development. } 8.Nc3!? c6 { 8...Ng3+? 9.Kg1 Nxh1 10.Nd5+- } 9.Bc4 Ng3+ 10.Kg1 Nxh1 11.Kxh1= $13 ) Qg5 
9. Nf5 c6 ( 9...g6!? 10.h4! Qf6 11.Nc3 Bb7 $13 ) 
10. g4?! ( 10.Ba4! g6 11.Ng3 $14 { That is one interesting move. } ) Nf6 
11. Rg1 { Brilliant idea! White is just letting the bishop hang. Black should not have accepted the Trojan bishop. } cxb5? ( 11...h5 $15 ) 
12. h4! Qg6 
13. h5! Qg5 
14. Qf3! { White is a full piece down. The problem for Black is that the queen may be trapped soon. } Ng8 { Awful! Black wants to keep extra material. There was no other way except this 'beautiful' move. } 
15. Bxf4! Qf6 
16. Nc3! Bc5 { It is already too late to develop the pieces! } 
17. Nd5 ( { • } 17.d4+- ) ( { • } 17.Nxb5+- ) Qxb2 
18. Bd6! { All the commentators, including Garry Kasparov himself, said this was a mistake. I am grateful that this 'mistake' occurred. Modern engines proved the genius of Adolf Anderssen! It turns out that White was winning after all. } ( { • } 18.Re1+- { This move was winning. White simply has too many pieces involved in the game. However, we would not have had the immortal game then. :-) } ) ( { • } 18.d4+- ) ( { • } 18.Be3+- ) Bxg1? ( { The consensus among Steinitz, Euwe, Huebner (who analyzed this game for Chessbase), Kasparov (who analyzed this game for his famous book series 'My great Predecessors') was that Black was ok in the following line. To be honest with you, the first time I analyzed this position with Stockfish, I made the same mistake too... } 18...Qxa1+ 19.Ke2 Qb2 20.Kd2! { 20.Bxc5? Leads only to a draw 20...Qxc2+□ 21.Kf1□ Qxc5□ 22.Qf4!? White is a rook and bishop down but the attack is strong. The approximate variation that could happen goes something like this. 22...d6!? 22...f6 23.Nd6+ Kd8 24.Nf7+ Ke8 25.Nd6+= 23.Nxd6+ Kd7 24.Qxf7+ Kxd6 25.Qf8+ Kc6 26.Qxc8+ Kd6 27.Qf8+ Kc6 28.Nb4+ Kb6 29.Nd5+ Kc6= } 20...Bxg1 { 20...g6 21.Bxc5! Kasparov analyzes this move. 21.Re1!? Bb7 22.Bxc5 gxf5 23.exf5+ Kd8 24.Bb6+!! axb6 25.Qe3+- Black has to give up the queen to avoid the quick checkmate. 25...Qb4+□ 26.Nxb4+- 21...gxf5 22.exf5+- Leads to a winning attack for White. }{ 20...Bb6 21.Bb4! Kd8 22.h6+- } 21.e5 { Kasparov thought that Black could fight for the advantage after } 21...Bb7 { 21...Ba6 It takes Stockfish some time to find the correct move. In this analysis, Kasparov considered only the logical 22. Nxg7+ 22.Bb4!! Backward move! 22...Nh6 22...Qxe5 23.Nd6+ Qxd6 24.Bxd6 Nc6 25.Nc7+ Kd8 26.Qxf7!? Nge7 27.Nxa8 White wins back the material and continues the attack. There is no coordination between Black's pieces whatsoever. 27...Bb7 28.Nc7 Bb6 28...b4 29.Qxg7+- 29.Nxb5+- 23.Nd6+ Kf8 24.g5+- All the pieces are aimed at the king. Black has to give a lot to not get checkmated. } 22.Nxg7+! Kd8 23.Qxf7 Be3+ 24.Nxe3 Ne7 25.Qf6!! { This quiet backward move leads to a winning attack for White. It is a fantastic situation - White is two rooks down, and yet the attack is overwhelming. } { Kasparov's analysis goes 25.Qxe7+? Kc8 $13 With unclear consequences. }{ 25.Bxe7+ Kc8 } 25...Qxa2 { 25...Kc8 26.Ngf5!! Another backward move! 26...Bf3 White is now taking back some of the material. 26...Nxf5 27.Qxh8 27.Qxh8+ Kb7 28.Bxe7+- Suddenly, White is only an exchange down and the attack is still in progress. } 26.Bxe7+! Kc7 27.Ngf5 Nc6 28.Qd6+! Kc8 { 28...Kb6 29.Nd5+ Ka5 29...Ka6 30.Nb4++- Wins the full queen. 30.Nd4!? Rac8 30...Nxd4 31.Qc7+ Ka4 31...Ka6 32.Nb4 32.Nc3 31.Nb3+ Ka6 31...Ka4 32.Nc3 32.Nb4++- } 29.Nd5! Qa5+ 30.Ke2! { Black is paralyzed! The attack is unstoppable. For example, } 30...Nd8 { 30...Re8 31.e6! dxe6 32.Qxe6+ Kb8 33.Bd6++- }{ 30...Nd4+ 31.Nxd4 Bxd5 32.Qxd5 Rb8 33.e6+- } 31.Qb8+!! { That is just brilliant! } { Also leads to a mate 31.Bxd8+- } 31...Kxb8 { 31...Rxb8 32.Nd6 } 32.Bd6+ Kc8 33.Nfe7 ) 
19. e5! { It turns out that White had three more winning alternatives! } ( { • } 19.Re1+- ) ( { • } 19.Qd1+- ) ( { • } 19.Rd1+- ) Qxa1+ 
20. Ke2! { Some sources say that the game ended here with Black's resignation. } Na6 ( 20...Ba6 { Was the last try. } 21.Nc7+! Kd8 22.Nxa6! { Now Bc7+ and Qxa8 are huge threats. } 22...Qc3 { 22...Bb6 23.Qxa8+- } 23.Bc7+! Qxc7 { 23...Kc8 24.Nd6 }{ 23...Ke8 24.Nd6++- } 24.Nxc7! { White is winning a lot of material } 24...Kxc7 { 24...Nc6 25.Nxa8+- White is already materially up! } 25.Qxa8 { With a crushing attack. The material is almost equal, and yet all Black's pieces are not coordinated. } 25...Nh6 26.Nd6+- ) 
