1. Nf3 } d5 
2. d4 Nf6 
3. c4 c6 
4. Nc3 { Both players were fighting for the center and developing pieces until now. } e6 { I find it difficult to give an easy explanation on why Black plays c7-c6 and then e7-e6 in this line. The combination of these moves does not make sense from an opening principles perspective. Why do we need c7-c6? Well, the deep reason is that the main problem for Black is the bishop on c8. It is restricted by its pawns. The way that Black can handle this problem is by dxc4, followed by b7-b5 and Bc8-b7. This plan loses time and creates some weaknesses. Which is why I would not necessarily recommend it to beginners or casual players. } 
5. Bg5 { Carslen develops anotehr piece. } h6 
6. Bh4 { White is maintaining the pin and keeping a strong bishop. } Qb6? } { Black is trying to exploit the weak b2-pawn. That is a typical problem with developing the queenside bishop. The queen is vulnerable and misplaced here. Black should have aimed for the 'crazy' main line or at least developed the bishop to e7 to prepare castling kingside. } ( { Here is a 'crazy' main line: } 6...dxc4 7.e4 g5 8.Bg3 b5 $13 { Black wins a pawn at a cost of continuous problems with the king (after g7-g5 and b7-b5 it will not have a safe place to stat), and the missing center. One has to be a sophisticated player to handle these problems and keep an extra pawn. } ) 
7. Qc2 { Magnus develops another piece. } Ne4?! { Black moves the piece again... } 
8. e3 { Magnus continues the development. } Bb4 
