{ That was one memorable game of mine. Round 4 of Qatar Masters Open 2014. Giri, Kramnik, Mamedyarov, Vachier-Lagrave, and Ding were the top players. Although, Ding Liren was not as strong as he is right now. His rating was 'only' 2730. In the previous round, I won against Pentala Harikrishna so now I was playing on the first board! Only four people had 3 out of 3! I was nervous and lost horribly! Enjoy! } 1. e4 } c6 
2. d4 d5 
3. e5 } { The pawn on e5 prevents an easy development for the g8-knight. There is no good way to complete the development quickly anymore. } Bf5 { The main line of Caro-Kan defense. } 
4. h4 { The idea of this odd-looking move is to prevent e7-e6 which is the logical next step for Black. } c5 { This was the sideline I prepared when I studied Caro-Kann. Nowadays, Stockfish already rates the move as suspicious. Back then Komodo was the strongest engine and it was not so pessimistic. The idea of this move is to 'punish' the h2-h4 move by hitting the center. The problem is that Black will not be able to quickly finish the development because of that pawn on e5. } ( { • } 4...e6?? 5.g4! Be4 6.f3! Bg6 7.h5+- { The bishop is trapped! When developing your queenside bishop, you should be watching out for such idea. } ) ( { • The main move for Black is } 4...h5 ) ( { • The second most-played move is } 4...h6 { preparing a safe square for the bishop. } ) 
5. dxc5 Nc6 } 
6. Bb5 } ( { White has many logical strong options. The check does not win material. } 6...Qa5+ 7.Nc3! d4? 8.Bxc6+!? bxc6 9.Qxd4+- ) 
7. Ne2 { This move was not in my file! That was one smart decision! Usually, grandmasters want to run away from their opponent's preparation with minimum damage to the position. This move accomplishes that! } ( { • } 7.Bf4 $16 ) ( { • } 7.Qxd5 $16 ) ( { • } 7.Nc3 $16 { Stockfish likes this one the most. } ) ( { • } 7.Nf3 $14 ) Qxe5 ( { I decided to win back the crucial pawn. I thought that it would help develop my kingside. Boy, was I wrong! I should have continued the development! My bishop on f5 was no longer in danger. } 7...e6! 8.Bxc6+!? bxc6 9.Qd4 { I think I did not like this line. } 9...Bxc2 $14 { I do not have space and it is difficult to develop pieces. Nevertheless, I should have done this. The material is equal, the position is closed. } ) 
8. Bf4! ( { The bishop gets out with a tempo. Another strong alternative was } 8.Nbc3!? { White gets a winning advantage with some energetic play. } 8...e6 { 8...Nf6 9.Bf4 Qe6 10.O-O !? How does Black finish the development now? 10...g6 11.Nd4!? Qd7 White has domination on the dark squares with any sensible move. The strongest would be a fun one. 12.a4!? Bg7 13.a5 a6 14.Bxc6 bxc6 15.Na4+- The knights and the bishop are on fire! } 9.Bf4! Qf6 10.Bg5! Qe5 { 10...Qg6 11.Nf4+- Traps the queen. } 11.Qd4! Qxd4 { White has an enormous lead in development for free! 11...Qc7 12.Ng3+- 12.O-O-O $16 } 12.Nxd4+- ) Qxb2 
9. Nbc3! } { Anish is giving up more material for even faster development! } Nf6? ( { It is too late to develop pieces. White is too much ahead in development. I should have gone all-in with } 9...Bxc2 10.Qxd5! { We both calculated this line and both concluded that White has a winning advantage. } 10...Qxa1+ 11.Kd2! { Centralizing the king! :-) } 11...Rd8 { The best try. } { The greedy capture would have led to a quick checkmate. 11...Qxh1 12.Bxc6+! bxc6 13.Qxc6+ Kd8 14.Bc7+ Kc8 15.Bb6+ Kb8 16.Qc7 }{ I do not recall calculating this interesting trick. I wonder if Giri saw it during the game. 11...Be4 12.Qxe4□ 12.Nxe4?? Qb2+-+ 12...Qb2+ 12...O-O-O+ 13.Kc2 Qxh1 14.Bxc6 The king is not safe after castle! 14...bxc6 15.Qxc6 13.Ke1 Black has an extra exchange and a pawn. 13...Qa1+ 13...Rc8 14.Bc1!? Qa1 Transposes. 14.Bc1! Rc8 White cannot castle and Black has an extra exchange and a pawn. The only problem is that it is White to move! Well, also the queen on a1 cannot breathe... White has many winning options. For example, 15.Qb4 15.Kd2!? Nf6 16.Qb4 e6 17.Bxc6+ bxc6 17...Rxc6 18.Qxb7 Rxc5 19.Qb8+ Kd7 20.Rd1+- 18.Kc2 Nd5 19.Qb7 Rc7 20.Qb8+ Kd7 21.Rd1+- 15...e6 16.Bxc6+ bxc6 17.Qb7+- The queen comes in first. White wins the c6 pawn (in case of Rc8-d8), or the knight is coming to e4-d6 (in case of Ng8-e7), or the rook comes through h1-h3-d3(in case of Ke8-d8) } 12.Qxd8+ Kxd8 13.Rxa1 { White is only one pawn but all the pieces are ready for action! } 13...e5!? { Counterattacking the bishop while opening a bishop of mine. This would be a somewhat better try. White is still winning but the pass there is not crystal clear. } ) ( { Here is the line I calculated and rejected } 9... Bc2.13...Bf5 14.Bxc6! bxc6 15.Nd4! Bd7 { 15...e5 16.Nxc6++- } 16.Rb1+- { The rook just comes in! } ) 14.Bxc6! bxc6 { 14...exf4 15.Bxb7 Bf5 16.c6+- This passed pawn is too powerful with knight support on the way. } 15.Bxe5 Bf5 16.Nd4 Ne7 { At least some pieces are developed and the rook cannot join the at