16. Nb5 } Bc5 { Congratulations! I developed my bishop! The only problem that I did not solve was my king's safety... Bear in mind that a castle does not necessarily mean safety for your king! } 
17. Ned4 } Qf6 
18. Qf3+- } { The queen is coming with a tempo. It will go to f4-b8 or c3. Either way, White is completely winning. I finally resigned. What did I do wrong? I decided to eat pawns! I should have developed my pieces instead! Giri once again proved that he is a world-class grandmaster. } 1-0

[Event "Opening Compass for Black and White"]
[White "3) Castle"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Date "2023.08.14"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/28896722"]
[ECO "C11"]

1. e4 { Why do we need to castle? Well, let us take it from the top again. We have already established the importance of central control and the importance of developing your pieces. It is time to talk about the king. Once your pawns go to fight for the center, your king is left with no cover. That could lead to annoying checks on the open e-file or the e1/a5 (a4/e8) diagonals. You will see the examples throughout the chapter. The king is the most vulnerable piece. It needs your protection almost all the time. Usually, the only way to get your king into a safe shelter is to castle. This magical move will also develop your rook from the corner!

I would say that quick castling is good in 95% of cases. The main exception would be a completely closed center. For example, advanced variation in French defense or many lines in the KID. If the center is closed, then the king is barely exposed to any threats. For example, in some KID lines White never castles. The king stays in the center and White could actually advance pawns on both sides of the board. Another not obvious exception would be when castling would actually put the king under possible attack. For example, in the French defense pawn structure the Bxh7 sacrifice (so-called Greek gift sacrifice) often leads to a win. Why is that? Because the e5-pawn prevents the knight from going to f6. This leaves the king covered only by pawns. White, on the other hand, has the queen, the knight, and two bishops ready to launch the attack.

The main motivation behind castling should be the king's safety and the rook's development. So you should not castle just for the sake of castling. Sometimes, quite rarely, you do not need to do that. I would say that on the first level, you should castle quickly all the time. With time you would be able to tell when castling could be delayed or dropped altogether.

I also like to draw analogies with mathematics - another field close to my heart. When we study numbers we are taught that you can add them and you can subtract a smaller one from a bigger one. We are also taught that odd numbers are not divisible by two and that you cannot take a square root of two, for example. Is that true? I do not think so! It is just at this stage a student must comprehend and understand simple addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division. When he is confident in his knowledge, he will be ready to expand it to negative numbers, rational numbers (fractions), and irrational numbers (like the square root of 2).

Once he is comfortable in this field, the next step would be complex numbers that solve the problem of square-rooting negative numbers. Then it turns out that there are different types of infinities. Some infinities are more infinite than others, and so on...

What I am trying to say is that it is a journey. First, you learn and understand some rules. Once you deeply understand the rules, you will be able to tell when you can break those rules to expand your understanding of chess, like we expand our understanding of mathematics. For now, the main goal is to follow the principle and understand the underlying reasons behind it. } } ( 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.e4 d6 5.f3 O-O 6.Be3 e5 7.d5 c5 { There is no need to castle anymore! The position is completely closed. The king is safe and the h1-rook could be developed by the h-pawn movement. For example, } 8.g4 $16 { It would be a big strategical mistake to castle short now. 8.Bd3 Nh5 9.Nge2 f5 10.O-O ? f4! Black is launching an attack on the kingside due to space advantage on that part of the board. Castling long was much safer because White has a space advantage there. 11.Bf2 Bf6!? 12.a3 Bh4 13.b4 Bxf2+ 14.Rxf2 Nd7 15.Rf1 g5 16.h3 Kh8 17.Rb1 Rg8 $17 White cannot stop the g4 breakthrough. Black will either sacrifice the piece or slowly prepare it with Nh5-f6, h5, g4. } 8...Nbd7? 9.h4+- { Stockfish already gives the decisive advantage to White! White is launching the kingside attack. Black has no counterplay. } ) e6 
2. d4 d5 
3. Nc3 Nf6 
4. e5 Nfd7 
5. Nf3 Bb4 
6. Bd3 O-O?? 
7. Bxh7+! } { The move is possible because there is no knight on f6. } Kxh7 
8. Ng5+! } { The bishop supports the knight, and going to h6 with the king is a suicide. } Kg8 ( 8...Kg6 { White has multiple winning options. } 9.h4+- { The h-pawn and the rook are joining the attack. } ) 
9. Qh5! } { Mate in one is coming. The crucial moment is that there is no Nf6! } Re8 
10. Qxf7+ } Kh8 
11. Qh5+ Kg8 
12. Qh7+ Kf8 
13. Qh8+ Ke7 
14. Qxg7 *

