1. e4 } c5 
2. Nf3 g6 
3. c3 } { White is preparing to conquer the center. Usually, only White can afford to do that in the opening. This move does not help with the development, it actually makes it harder. That is what I mean when Isay 'White can afford to do that'. } b6?! { Black is delaying the fight for the center as well as the castle. } ( { • } 3...d5!? { Black should have fought for the center. Also, this move helps develop the bishop. } 4.exd5 Qxd5 { This queen development is justified exactly because White put the pawn on c3. Otherwise, the queen would have been harrassed in Scandinavian style with Nc3! } 5.d4 Bg7 $13 ) ( { • } 3...Nf6!? { This move would have secured the castle. Well, Black would lose control over the center. } 4.e5 Nd5 5.d4 cxd4 6.cxd4 Bg7 $14 { White gets the center but at least Black's king will go to relative safety soon. } ) ( { • } 3...Bg7!? 4.d4 cxd4 5.cxd4 d5 6.e5 $16 { White is taking away the crucial f6 square. Black will have to go to h6 (knight on the rim is grim!). } ) 
4. d4! { White gets the center. } Bb7 
5. Bc4! } { That is one active bishop! It is typically a weak spot when the king is not castled. It is also a strong way to indirectly protect the pawn on e4. } ( 5.Bd3 $16 ) d5? { Too late to fight for the center! } ( { • This move would not lose so quickly. Black could still hold. } 5...Bg7 $16 ) ( { • } 5...Nf6? 6.e5+- { That is the point of getting the center - you can kick your opponent's pieces away! } ) ( { • } 5...Bxe4? 6.Ng5! { Almost winning. } { 6.Bxf7+!? Kxf7 7.Ng5+ Kg7 8.Nxe4 $16 The king on g7 will not be safe! } 6...d5 7.Bb5+! { 'How are you doing?' the bishop asks. } 7...Nd7 8.dxc5! { 8.Nxe4!? dxe4 9.dxc5 bxc5 10.Na3! Black cannot develop pieces naturally anymore. 10...Bg7? 11.Qa4! Ngf6 12.Bg5+- } 8...bxc5? 9.f3 Bxb1 { 9...Bf5 10.Qxd5+- } 10.Qxd5! e6 11.Bxd7+ Qxd7 12.Qxa8++- { Wins everything. } ) 
6. exd5 Bxd5? ( { That was the final mistake. } 6...Nf6 { White wins the pawn but at least Black will castle after Bg7. } 7.dxc5 bxc5 8.Bg5 Bg7 9.Qb3 Qc7+- ) 
7. Qa4+! { The punishment for keeping the king in the center is approaching! Also, White is better developed (queen+knight+bishop). } Bc6 ( { • } 7...Qd7? 8.Qxd7+ Nxd7 9.Bxd5+- { Wins the piece. } ) ( { • } 7...Nc6 8.Bb5!? { 8.Ne5+- } 8...Rc8 9.Ne5 Qc7 10.Bf4!? { Black is paralyzed. } 10...Bh6 11.Bg3+- { Black is collapsing on one of those diagonals. } ) 
8. Ne5!! } { Brilliant! } Qc7 ( 8...Bxa4 9.Bxf7 { This beautiful line was left behind the scenes. This would never have happened if Black castled the king or at least developed the f8-bishop. } ) 
9. Nxc6 ( 9.Bxf7++- { Wins the pawn and kicks the king. } ) Nxc6 
10. d5+- } ( { The knight is busted. Black resigned. } 10.Bf4+- ) 1-0

