1. e4 } c5 
2. Nf3 a6 { This move should look weird to you. It does not help with the development or with the center. However, there is an idea behind it. } 
3. c3 { I decided to prepare d2-d4. I wanted to have two pawns in the very center of the board. White is getting an improved Alapin variation(2.c3 is Alapin. Obviously, the inclusion of Nf3 and a6 is in White's favor in all the lines). } ( { • The main idea behind 2...a6 is revealed in the following line. } 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 { 5.e5?? Qa5+ 6.Nc3 Qxe5+ $17 Black wins the full pawn. } 5...e5 $13 { Now, the knight cannot go to b5 which is the usual response to the e7-e5 pawn move. So actually, the deep idea behind 2... a6 is to fight for the center! } ) ( { • } 3.c4!? { That would be a great alternative. White is putting another pawn in the center. } 3...Nc6 4.d4! cxd4 5.Nxd4 $14 ) d5 
4. exd5 Qxd5 { Developing a queen early is usually justified if the knight cannot attack it. That is exactly the case here! My pawn on c3 is preventing Nb1-c3. } 
5. d4 { My pawn goes to the center. } cxd4?! 
6. cxd4! { This exchange helps me develop my other knight. } e6 
7. Nc3! { Now, I have control over the center and easy development. } Bb4 } 
8. Bd3 { Here comes the bishop. Castle is next. } Nf6 
9. O-O } Bxc3 
10. bxc3 { Thank you for the two-bishop advantage! Also, thank you for improving my pawn structure! Now I can push the pawns! } b5 } { Black is trying to prevent my pawn advance. } 
11. a4 ( 11.Ba3+- { That was one typical way of preventing the castle! There is no immediate win. It is just that the king on e8 is forever weak and the rook on h8 is not entering the game whatsoever. } ) Bb7 ( { Black should have sacrifices the pawn. } 11...O-O ! 12.axb5 axb5 13.Rxa8 Qxa8 14.Bxb5 Bb7 $16 { At least the king is safe and Black has some active pieces. } ) 
12. Ba3+- } { No castle today! Unless Black is ready to castle long :-) That is a joke because there are no pawns to guard the king on the queenside! That would be like walking into the fire! } g5 { Desperate attempt! It is a typical intimidating strategy. You have to keep calm. It turns out that even if the pawn gets to g5 we could move the knight to h4 or e1. } 
13. axb5 axb5 ( 13...g4 14.c4+- { Ruining the battery on the long diagonal. My knight would triumphantly jump to e5. } ) 
14. Re1 Nbd7 ( 14...g4 15.Re5+- { I planned to kick the queen out of the center. } ) 
15. Bf1 } { With this move, I am trying to show my opponent that his attack has failed. Mine has not started yet. But it is coming! } Ne4 ( 15...g4 16.Ne5+- ) 
16. Qb1 } Ra4 { My opponent is preventing Qb4. Luckily, I have more threats than that. The thing is that I am using ALL my pieces in the game. And Black does not! Do not believe me? Ask the rook on h8! } ( { • } 16...Nxc3 17.Qb4+- { The checkmate is coming! } ) ( { • Here is the tactical justification. } 16...g4 17.c4! { 17.Ne5+- } 17...bxc4 18.Bxc4 Qxc4 19.Qxb7 Qd5 20.Qb4 { 20.Qxd5!? exd5 21.Nd2+- } 20...Rxa3 21.Qxa3!? gxf3 22.Qa8+ Ke7 23.Qxh8+- ) 
17. Rxe4!? ( { • } 17.Qxb5+- ) ( { • } 17.Bxb5+- ) Qxe4 
18. Qxb5 } Rxa3 ( 18...Bc6 19.Qxg5+- { The queen is coming to say 'hi' to the king! } ) 
19. Rxa3 f6 } { I have an extra pawn but I have more active pieces :-) } 
20. c4 } { Too bad that back in 2006, I did not study my Chessable course about Initiative! If I did, I would have known that if you have three good-looking forcing moves then you do not need to look any further! In this case, the good-looking forcing moves are Ra7, Bd3, and Nd2. The irony is that not only one of these moves are the best but All of them are the best! In my defense, my move was also winning and it did create a threat (21. Re3!) } ( { • A more aggressive win would be } 20.Bd3!? Qf4 { 20...Qc6 21.Ra7+- }{ 20...Qd5 21.Ra7+- } 21.Qxb7 Qc1+ 22.Bf1 Qxa3 23.Qc8++- ) ( { • } 20.Ra7+- ) ( { • } 20.Nd2+- ) Qc6 ( 20...Bc6 21.Re3! { This was my plan! } 21...Bxb5 { 21...Qxe3 22.Qxc6! Qa3 23.Qc8+ Ke7 24.Qxh8+- With an extra piece. } 22.Rxe4! Ba4 23.Rxe6++- { Two connected passed pawns would easily win the game. } ) 
21. Qb4 } { Still preventing castle! } Qc7 ( 21...Kf7 22.d5! exd5 23.cxd5 Qb6 { 23...Qxd5 24.Bc4+- The king is not safe on f7! } 24.Qxb6!? Nxb6 25.Ra7 Rb8 26.Ba6+- { Winning the bishop. } ) 
22. Ra7+- } { My opponent collapsed in a horrible position. I won the game because I prevented my opponent's castle. The rest was a matter of technique. } 1-0

