14. Ng3 ( 14.fxe4 Qh4 { Checkmate! } ) Qh4+! } 
15. Kg2 Rxg3+ } 
16. fxg3 Qxg3+ } 
17. Kh1 Qh3+ } 
18. Kg1 Bxe3+ 
19. Rf2 Bxf2 { Why did White lose so terribly? Well, the problems began when Black launched the attack. Why was the attack even possible? Well, the hook on h3 helped Black to open the g-file.

Why was the hook there? Well, the Bg4 pin was very annoying for White because there was no bishop on e2.

Why is there no bishop on e2? Because we want it to be active! Also, if White had another knight on d2 then the pin would not be a problem. Yes, but then Black could easily push d7-d5 and conquer the center!

We can continue this discussion but the bottom line would be that sometimes castling your king does not necessarily lead to safety. For example, in this particular line, I would suggest waiting for your opponent to castle or putting the bishop to e3 first. If the f-file opens up then the attack would not be successful. Also, such attacks usually do not work in an open position.

The only reason why Black could even think about moves like g7-g5 was the fact that the position was closed and it could not open any time soon (the d4 square was under Black's control). That is one of the reasons for putting the bishop to e3 - White would have the d3-d4 option available to them. } 
