10... Qe7?? } 
{ Black's king is castled and yet it is not safe at all! } 11. Qxh7+!! { Here is one thought. Try changing the move order when your idea consists of two moves (in this case, it is Nxf6 and Qxh7)! If your idea consists of three independent moves then you have six(!) different move orders to execute your idea! Think about that! Do not give up on an idea until you checked different move orders!

Another fun fact is that if somehow your idea consists of four independent moves then you have 24(!) different move orders! I love this kind of mathematics! You can look at it this way.

You have four objects (in this case, the objects are your moves) and you have four numbered boxes. You can put any object into any empty box. How many ways are there to put the objects into the boxes? The answer would be 4!=432*1=24 } ( 11.Nxf6+? gxf6 { This recapture was Black's idea. The pawn on h7 is under protection } 12.Nf3 Nc6 $14 { Black is ok. The attack is over. } ) Kxh7 
