13. Neg4+! } { One more check! } ( { Please note that } 13.Nfg4+?? { is a blunder, since Black's king can now hide on the h5-square, which is temporarily safe. } ) Kg5 
14. h4+! { A practical decision is to go for the line where your opponent has only moves. This way you can be certain that you are winning. } Kf4 { The only legal move. } 
15. g3+ Kf3 { Another only legal move. } 
16. Be2+! ( { • A faster checkmate would involve a quiet move like } 16.Kf1 gxf6 17.Nh2 { (• White could have castled the king just in case :-) } ) ( 16.O-O gxf6 17.Nh2 ) Kg2 { Once again, the only legal move. } 
17. Rh2+ Kg1 
18. Kd2 { One could argue that Black lost because of a blunder. That is true! However, what was the deeper fundamental reason for the existence of the combination? I would argue that the king was not safe because the f-pawn was missing! Black may have had a false sense of seсurity. White had four (!) pieces attacking the king and there was no f7 pawn.

Also, the king would have been in big trouble if White were to castle long. Actually, Black's king would feel much safer on the queenside. After all, many pawns and pieces were waiting for his arrival. I think Edward Lasker understood that and decided to prevent long castle with 9. Ne5!? By the way, the rules of this game were that neither player exceeds the total time of the other by more than five minutes at any stage. It makes Edward Lasker's masterpiece even more impressive! } *

