Another fun fact is that if somehow your idea consists of four independent moves then you have 24(!) different move orders! I love this kind of mathematics!

You can look at it this way. You have four objects (in this case, the objects are your moves) and you have four numbered boxes. You can put any object into any empty box. How many ways are there to put the objects into the boxes? The answer would be 4!=432*1=24 } ( 11.Nxf6+? gxf6 { This recapture was Black's idea. The pawn on h7 is under protection } 12.Nf3 Nc6 $14 { Black is ok. The attack is over. } ) Kxh7 
12. Nxf6+! } { Double check! The only way to deal with a double check is to run with your king. } Kh6 ( 12...Kh8 13.Ng6 { That is one beautiful checkmate! This checkmate would be impossible if the pawn was still on f7! } ) 
13. Neg4+! } { One more check! } Kg5 
14. h4+! { A practical decision is to go for the line where your opponent has only moves. This way you can be certain that you are winning. } ( { I remember solving this puzzle when I was a child. I remember how proud I was to find a faster checkmate than the one delivered in the game! } 14.f4+! Kxf4 { 14...Kh4 15.g3+! Kh3 16.Bf1+! Bg2 17.Nf2 } 15.g3+! Kg5 { 15...Kf3 16.O-O My solution also had a castle checkmate. } 16.h4 { The king is packed into a very nice box! } ) Kf4 { The only legal move. } 
15. g3+ Kf3 { Another only legal move. } 
16. Be2+! ( { • A faster checkmate would involve a quiet move like } 16.Kf1 gxf6 17.Nh2 { (• White could have castled the king just in case :-) } ) ( 16.O-O gxf6 17.Nh2 ) Kg2 { The only legal move. } 
17. Rh2+ Kg1 
18. Kd2 { One could argue that Black lost because of a blunder. That is true! However, what was the deeper fundamental reason for the existence of the combination? I would argue that the king was not safe because the f-pawn was missing! Black may have had a false sense of seсurity. White had four (!) pieces attacking the king and there was no f7 pawn. Also, the king would have been in big trouble if White were to castle long. Actually, Black's king would feel much safer on the queenside.

After all, many pawns and pieces were waiting for his arrival. I think Edward Lasker understood that and decided to prevent long castle with 9. Ne5!? By the way, the rules of this game were that neither player exceeds the total time of the other by more than five minutes at any stage. It makes Edward Lasker's masterpiece even more impressive! } 1-0

[Event "Opening Compass for Black and White"]
[White "4) One Tempo Tragedy"]
[Black "Develop as quickly as possible!"]
[Date "2023.08.14"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/28897723"]

1. -- { The point of this chapter is for you to feel a sense of urgency when it comes to developing your pieces. Generally speaking, you should not waste any time when it comes to your development. Ideally, your development should take the least amount of moves possible.

Here, you will find examples where Black needed just one more move to make the position ok. You should also get a sense of urgency when it comes to punishing your opponent's mistakes. You should feel the energy with which you should play to benefit from your opponent's delays.

If I had to summarize previous chapters in a few sentences, it would go something like this. Center! Development! Castle! As quickly as possible!

If I had more sentences, then I would elaborate something like this. You need to put your pawns in the center because it is the most important part of the board. The pawns provide you with space behind them and leave less space for your opponent. You should develop pieces to win the game. The piece is active when it is attacking the center or your opponent's piece. Castle usually (not all the time!) provides shelter for your king, and develops the rook. You should do all of that quickly because time is money! } } *

