1. d4 { This was a memorable tournament and a memorable game of mine. This was the last round of the 22nd Drezden AMD Open. Six grandmasters were leading the tournament (Shankland, Meier, Bluebaum, Vorobiov, Teske, and myself) with six points out of eight. I needed the win to fight for the first prize. } } d5 
2. Nf3 Nf6 
3. c4 dxc4 { Queen's gambit accepted. } 
4. e3 } { Black usually cannot hold that pawn. } e6 { This move was the surprise. Before this game, my opponent chose mostly the 4... Bg4 line. I was prepared there. Now, I was completely on my own! I was on my own on move four! Well, I did see many games in the line but I had no experience myself. That is why I decided to stick to common sense moves. } 
5. Bxc4 c5 { Black is fighting for the center with another pawn. } 
6. O-O Nc6 
7. Nc3 { So far the moves are natural. Both sides fight for the center and develop pieces. } a6 { This one goes against the rules. Black is delaying the development of the f8 bishop. The idea is to go b7-b5 and develop the other bishop to b7 first. Why first? Because Black wants White to capture the pawn on c5 then the bishop would develop automatically without any loss of time. } 
8. a4 { I decided to keep it simple. Does Black want to go b7-b5? Well, I am stopping it. The downside is the weakened b4 square for the c6-knight. } cxd4 
9. exd4 { The previous exchange helped me develop my bishop. } Be7 
10. Bg5 } { I tried to develop my pieces to the most active squares. } O-O { In my mind, I had the following set-up: Qe2+Rad1+Rfe1. Why did I not decide to put the rook to the only open file? Well, the answer is not obvious. Generally speaking, exchanging pieces favors Black in this pawn structure because Black does not have enough space. That is why I wanted to avoid the c-file to avoid exchanging rooks.

Also, two main plans when you have an isolated pawn are the kingside attack or the d4-d5 breakthrough. In both cases, I will need my rooks on the central files. Why did I choose to put the queen to e2, not d2? Because the queen does not like to be bothered. In my mind, I saw the rook on d8. That would make my queen uncomfortable.

Also, it is quite typical that the bishop on e7 will become a good target after the d4-d5 break. } 
11. Re1 } { I could not go Qe2 yet so I chose this move. } Bd7 { My opponent continues to develop. } 
12. Qe2 } Rc8 
13. Rad1 } { I certainly completed the development. There were different options for every side almost on every. } h6 
14. Bh4 { I decided to keep more pieces due to my space advantage. } Nh5? { The only (!) mistake in the game! My opponent spent A LOT of time on this move. The problem was that his rook on f8 was not taking part in the action. He did not complete his development! Now, it was my turn to dive into the calculation to prove my opponent's mistake } ( { • My opponent should have completed development with } 14...Re8 $14 ) ( { • Developing the queen was also not a bad idea. } 14...Qa5 $14 ) ( { • It was also a good idea to improve the rook and the knight in one go. } 14...Nb4 $14 ) 
15. d5! } { This typical move opens the files and diagonals for my pieces. } Nf4 { My oponent planned this intermediate jum in advance. } ( 15...Bxh4? { White has two crushing options. The most obvious one } 16.dxc6! { And the more winning one. 16.dxe6! Nf4 16...fxe6 17.Bxe6++- Wins material with a tempo. 17.Rxd7+- 17.exf7+! Kh8 18.Qe4+- This is more winning according to Stockfish. Black cannot handle all the threats. } 16...Rxc6 17.Ne5+- { Black would not handle all three threats at once. White wins material. } ) ( { Here is the line I calclated. } 15...exd5 16.Bxe7! Nxe7 17.Qxe7 Rxc4 { 17...Qxe7 18.Rxe7+- } 18.Nxd5 { I saw that Black has no good moves. For example, } 18...Re8 19.Qxd8!? Rxd8 20.Nb6 { 20.Ne5! I saw that this one was winning. White wins with some combination of Nxd7 and Ne7+. } 20...Rc7 21.Ne5 Nf6 22.Nexd7 Nxd7 { I also saw this tricky line. It seems that White is dominant because of the pin. White has time to slowly double the rooks. } 23.Rd2!? { 23.Re7?? This logical move fails to the brilliant 23...Nf8!! Breaking the double pin! Now White has to be careful! The only move is 24.Ree1= } 23...Kf8 24.Red1 Ke8 25.a5+- { Black will run out of moves soon. } ) 
16. Qe3! } { The only move that leads to a win. } exd5 ( { I also saw } 16...Nxd5 17.Bxd5! { The only winning move. } { 17.Nxd5? exd5 18.Bxe7 Nxe7 19.Qxe7 Rxc4= } 17...exd5 { 17...Bxh4 18.Bxc6! Rxc6 19.Nxh4! Qxh4 20.Rxd7+- With an extra knight. } 18.Bxe7! { The bishop on e7 really needed the rook next to it! } 18...Nxe7 19.Qxe7+- { With an extra piece. } ) 
17. Qxf4! { The only winning move. Here is my funny story. After playing the move, I went to refresh myself. I came back, and my opponent played his next move and left. In the next several seconds, I was surprised (I thought this capture was easily winning for me, so I expected other moves), then I was shocked (I saw the obvious defense to my 'easy win'), disappointed (how could I miss that?), and then happy (I saw the refutation to the defense). This emotional journey felt like a rollercoaster ride. It all happened in my head in a matter of seconds... } dxc4 ( { • } 17...Bxh4 { I calculated this move. } 18.Nxh4 { 18.Nxd5 Bg5 19.Nxg5 hxg5 20.Qg3+- Stockfish gives a winning advantage here. Obviously, White's activity is strong but I did not see an exact threat. The engine is saying that a4-a5 is a threat... I am a human, not a robot so I chose another line. } 18...dxc4 19.Nf5 { This was my plan. I did not see how Black can possibly handle my threats. One of them would be Rxd7 followed by Qg4 (after that White either delivers checkmate on g7 or wins the queen with the discovered attack). } 19...Qc7 { The more winning Stockfish line would be } 20.Nxh6+! { I saw the following line. 20.Qxc7 Rxc7 21.Nd5 Bxf5 21...Rcc8 22.Nde7++- 22.Nxc7 $16 With material gains. } 20...Kh7 { 20...gxh6 21.Qxh6+- With a winning attack. } 21.Rd6+- { With a winning attack. } ) ( { • I was mostly expecting } 17...g5 18.Qg3! { I should have aimed all my forces at the king. The crushing forcing line goes like this: } { I saw a safe line to a big advantage. 18.Qd2 dxc4 19.Qxd7 Qxd7 20.Rxd7 gxh4 21.Rexe7 Nxe7 22.Rxe7+- The rook is active, and the knights are covering all the important squares. }{ 18.Bxg5+- }{ 18.Nxg5+- } 18...dxc4 19.Bxg5! hxg5 20.Nxg5! Bxg5 21.Rxd7! Qxd7 22.Qxg5+! Kh8 23.Re4! { The rook is delivering the vertical mate, and the knight on c3 takes care of the back rank. } ) 
18. Bxe7! { I played the move before my opponent returned. He instantly responded... } Nxe7 
19. Qd6+- { After this fork, my opponent started shaking his head because he also saw what I saw... Why did my opponent lose the game? Well, the fundamental reason was that he did not complete his development. He just needed to do one more move and then he would have been ready... After the win I joined Shankland and Meier on the stage. We shared the first prize and I joined the ELO 2600+ club for the first time in my life! } ( 19.Qd6! { I calculated this line when I played 15.d5! My line ended here with the conclusion that I win a piece because of the fork. I did not double-check the line at any point before. } 19...Be6 { I missed this one! My opponent saw it in advance! This simple move handles the fork! Imagine my disappointment! Luckily, I immediately saw the refutation. } 20.Rxe6! { This is the move that my opponent missed. This is the move he saw when I played the last move of the game. He immediately resigned. } 20...fxe6 21.Qxe6++- ) 1-0

[Event "Opening Compass for Black and White"]
[White "Opening Repertoire Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction to the Repertoire"]
[Date "2023.08.14"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/29127169"]

1. -- { I want to say a few words about the following repertoire for both colors. I did my best to suggest opening lines that would be consistent with the principles laid out before. We will fight for the center with both colors. We will do our best to develop pieces as quickly as possible. We will try to castle the king as quickly as possible. } ( { With White, we will be playing } 1.e4 { , since it means castling is one move closer. With Black, we will play 1...e5 or 1...d5 on the first move. Then we focus on castling the king, and then we could think about putting more pawns into the center while completing the development.

It will be much easier to follow the principles with White because of the extra tempo. It's much harder as Black, because White could create obstacles using that extra tempo.

I want to emphasize that the point of the repertoire is not an advantage for White, although you will get it in many lines, or equality for Black. The point is the consistency with the general principles. Also, I want you to understand every single move you play. There are many opening lines out there where moves are hard to understand. Our lines will not be like that.

I will also be giving some alternative lines and briefly explaining their pros and cons. The opening lines end when the mission of “Center+Development+Castle” is complete or almost complete. The goal is for you to start the game decently with proper priorities in mind.

Let me also explain why certain sidelines are analyzed in-depth when often the main lines have much less representation. As you know, the goal of this repertoire is for you to be able to implement the principles explained before. More often than not, dubious or rare lines prevent us from naturally developing our pieces. The King’s Gambit, Danish Gambit, Vienna Game, and others are examples of problems when playing with the Black pieces. I wanted you to know what to do there and why.

With White, Sicilian was the most challenging. You can read the challenges I faced in the corresponding chapter. I also covered the Stafford Gambit, for example, since it is popular in the online blitz world. It literally never happened in a grandmaster classical game. Nevertheless, if you accept the sacrifice and simply follow the principles, you may get crushed.

I do not think that you need to study all the lines with equal dedication. Some lines are much more likely to happen in your games. I have selected more important lines with the “priority” badge. I think you should study those first. You have the option in your course settings to Learn & Review Priority variations only. Once you memorized and understood the main lines, you can go ahead and study other lines. Alternatively, you should study the sidelines when they suddenly happen in your games and you get in trouble in the opening.

Finally, I want to remind you that I end the lines in this repertoire when I do not see reasonable ways to prevent the completion of our development. In some cases, I had to continue the forcing line until it reaches a relatively quiet end. In some cases, I did not go for the most logical moves in a position. For example, I did not go for a quick castle in the London system because White often has a dangerous kingside attack there. Remember the “false principles” when the king only seems to be safe after the castle? In the Sicilian Najdorf, for example, I also explain how a sequence of logical moves can lead to a worse position.

This is not a “lifetime repertoire” opening course. My main goal was to emphasize the importance of all the principles and show ways for both colors to implement them in your games.

I hope you will enjoy studying the opening lines through the prism of the opening principles.

} ) } *

[Event "Opening Compass for Black and White"]
[White "Opening Repertoire Introduction"]
[Black "Opening Introduction: White"]
[Date "2023.08.14"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/29836784"]
[ECO "C42"]

{ First, I had to choose either 1.e4 or 1.d4. } 1. e4 } } { I decided to go for 1.e4 since it allows White to castle one move earlier. You just need to develop the knight and the bishop and you are ready to castle. The challenge with 1.e4 is that the pawn is not defended and Black has a lot more reasonable options than he he has after 1.d4. } ( { Here are my reasons why I did not go for 1.d4: } 1.d4 d5 2.c4 { If you fight for the center in this way, you have to be ready to lose this pawn (at least temporarily) after 2...dxc4, but even if Black chooses 2...e6 it is not that easy for White to castle quickly. } { I also thought about not playing c2-c4: 2.Nf3 Nf6 The problem is that if you are not going for c2-c4 then Black is going to play c7-c5! And then Black has two pawns in the center! 3.Bf4 3.e3 If you choose this move to castle quickly then your bishop on c1 is sad, and Black can go 3...c5 putting another pawn to the center. 3...c5 4.e3 Of course, there is the London System. But Black already has more pawns in the center, the pawn on b2 can be easily attacked with Qb6, and our king is still not close to castling because White often has to play c2-c3 first... } 2...e6 3.Nf3 Nf6 { How do you castle? If you go } 4.e3 { then you block the bishop on c1. In the Catalan, } { 4.g3 , you often lose the pawn on c4. Finally, if you decide to exchange pawns with 4.cxd5 and then develop the bishop to g5 with 4...exd5 5.Bg5 , then your king becomes exposed on the e1/a5 diagonal. Black can launch an attack with Bb4+c5+h6+g5+Ne4+Qa5. It is not easy to play with White when the king is exposed. } ) e5 ( 1...d5 2.exd5 c6 { Almnost nobody plays this line, but I had to cover it! Because if we take the pawn then Black gets easier development, and if we do not then Black has a very good position. } ) ( 1...c5 { The Sicilian was the main challenge. } 2.Nf3 { 2.Nc3 would lead to the closed Sicilian. Here White usually plays g2-g3 and it loses a tempo... Instead I prefer developing the f1-bishop quickly on its starting diagonal. } { 2.c3 The Alapin would be an easy choice, but it can lead to weird positions: 2...d5 3.exd5 Qxd5 4.d4 From the perspective of opening principles White has not developed a single piece yet... } 2...e6 { This move was the most challenging. White cannot develop the bishop now. } { 2...d6 3.d4 I could have gone for 3.Bb5+, but this would not be very consistent with our approach against 2...e6 for Black. 3...cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 a6 In the relevant chapter, I explain the difficulties I faced in picking a good line against the Najdorf. Basically, if you just follow opening principles you will often get a slightly worse position, and that is unacceptable for White. } 3.d4! { White cannot simply develop the bishop with } { 3.Bc4 because it runs into 3...d5! } ) 
2. Nf3 Nf6 } ( { After } 2...Nc6 3.Bc4 { I landed in the Italian because it is the most consistent with the principles. } { 3.Bb5 a6 4.Ba4 The problem with choosing Ruy Lopez was that often Black goes b7-b5 and we move the bishop to b3. So the question is: why didn't we put the bishop on the a2/g8 diagonal immediately? }{ 3.d4 I did not go for the Scotch, even though it is consistent with the principles, because of the following line: 3...exd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 5.Nxc6 bxc6 6.e5 Qe7 7.Qe2 Nd5 This is just a weird position. It is so weird that even 8.h4 is playable! How, on Earth, do I explain that from the perspective of opening principles? 5...Bb4 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.Bd3 d5 8.O-O O-O 9.exd5 cxd5 Suddenly Black controls the center. White has a tiny advantage but it is not consistent with our principles! I want White to have at least one pawn in the center. }) 
3. Nxe5 Nc6 { No serious player has played the Stafford Gambit in a classical game. However, it is very popular online. And the danger is that if you simply follow the principles you can lose quickly: } 
4. Nxc6 dxc6 
5. d3 Bc5 
6. Be2 h5 
7. O-O? { This is a mistake! } Ng4 } { With a dangerous attack for Black. } 
*

