{ From the start of the game Black is one tempo behind, so it is challenging to follow opening principles faithfully. Especially if White is creating obstacles on your opening journey.

There are some weird sidelines that I had to analyze deeply because they are forcing when some main lines end 'abruptly'. The sidelines often challenge the natural course of events with threats, sacrifices, and forcing moves. That is why I had to lend you a helping hand in those lines.

The main lines, on the other hand, often do not interfere with Black's natural development. In some lines, White would get a small advantage, but what does the computer's evaluation of +0.3 or +0.4 even mean? I honestly do not have a feeling of what 0.1, for example, looks like in practice...

The main goal I had for the Black repertoire was not to reach equality in all the lines, but rather to get an understandable setup where you understand where all the pieces go, you have a pawn in the center, and you can castle your king to safety. } 1. e4 } } { Here we have to go 1...c5 or 1...e5, as otherwise White would dominate in the center. } ( 1.d4 d5 { 1...Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 d5 The Grunfeld is the opening of today's top grandmasters, but I cannot recommend it to beginners for the following reason: 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.e4 Nxc3 6.bxc3 Black has no pawn in the center! Is this a bad opening? Of course not! It is just harder to play for Black, in my opinion. } 2.c4 { 2.e4 dxe4 We have to take, as otherwise White gets the center. 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.f3 You have to know what to do against this gambit as well. }{ 2.Bf4 Against the London system, I decided not to recommend a quick short castle because you can get under a weird attack that involves h2-h4... } 2...e6 { This is our main setup against 1.d4 openings: Nf6+Be7+O-O. Then we take care of the queenside with c7-c5, or b6+Bb7+Nbd7 and then c7-c5. } { 2...c6 The Slav is not consistent with our principles, as it does not help with development! It actually even takes the c6-square away from our knight. Is it bad? Of course not! But I simply could not suggest it as an opening choice aligned with our principles. }) ( 1.c4 e6 { Against the English, this move makes sure that we get our setup (d5+Nf6+Be7+O-O). } { 1...e5 Is the more logical move. However, I did not go there because I already faced some challenges creating a consistent approach for White against the Sicilian. After 1... e5 we would be getting a Sicilian with a tempo less! } ) e5 { This 'boring' classical move is my recommendation against 1.e4. It brings Black's castling one move closer. I had to analyze some rare (sometimes dubious) lines from White to make sure that you do not get in trouble in the opening. } ( 1...c5 { The downside to the Sicilian is that Black's castling is not happening anytime soon... } 2.Nf3 d6 { Black needs to prevent e4-e5 before putting a knight on f6. } { 2...Nc6 This move does not even prepare 3...Nf6 because e4-e5 is still possible. It means that that castling is still far away. 2...Nf6? You cannot develop the knight to f6 immediately because of 3.e5! } 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 e5? { This logical move leads to a very bad position after } 6.Bb5+! { 5...e6 6.g4! Also gives Black big problems. Once that pawn arrives on g5, the f6-knight will have to move to d6... }{ 5...a6 This is the move that introduces the Najdorf, preparing e7-e5 by preventing White from playing Bb5+. It violates the rules of quick development. It is, of course, a good move, but it is inconsistent with our principles. }{ 5...Nc6 6.Bg5 White castles long and our king will never be safe. }) ( 1...e6 2.d4 d5 3.e5 { This move is one of the problems with the French. After 3. e5 it is difficult for Black to develop the kingside and it is dangerous to castle there as well. } ) 
2. f4 } ( 2.d4 { You cannot play normal chess when White challenges the center like that... } 2...exd4 3.c3 { White can go for this gambit, for example. If we are not careful, we will lose the center or give White a dangerous lead in development. I had to cover this line, as I had to cover all the sidelines that interfere with our general principles. } ) ( 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.f4 { This line was another challenge. Black cannot just take the f4-pawn or continue their development as if nothing is happening. } ) d5 { If Black takes the f4-pawn then you lose the center. If you defend the pawn then you either lose the center or block your f8-bishop in. That's why I suggest this countergambit. } 
*

[Event "Opening Compass for Black and White"]
[White "5) White: 1.e4 vs. 1...c5 - 2...Nc6 & 2...d6"]
[Black "Kalashnikov #1"]
[Date "2023.08.14"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/28516096"]
[ECO "B32"]

1. e4 } c5 } { The Sicilian defense. There is a reason why this move is the most played one in the Mega Database. Black is somewhat preventing our pawn from going to d4. Meanwhile, Black keeps the options for his main central pawns flexible. This makes White's life much harder, as Black has a lot of different set-ups and it is not easy to find the answer to each of them. Also, unlike after 1...e5, the pawn on c5 will not be attacked after 2. Nf3. This gives Black many options.

I must admit that 1...c5 was the most challenging move to face when the goal was to follow the principles laid out before. With any other move besides 1...e5 or 1...c5, White can quickly put another pawn on d4. After that, White's development is easy and natural, as White has many options when two pawns are in the center.

With 1...e5, White develops the knight to f3 with a tempo. In the case of 2...Nc6 the bishop goes to c4 easily. After 1...c5, however, simply going for Nf3 and Bc4 is somewhat dangerous. Black has an option of playing a6+b5 or e7-e6, followed by d7-d5! Generally speaking, we cannot stop the latter.

That is why I decided to go for the main line 3. d4. After the knight reaches d4, White's development should be easy. Then I was thinking about the f1-bishop. If we put it on c4 then it becomes extremely vulnerable to various attacks (a6+b5, e6+d5, Qd8-c7, Nb8-c6-e5(a5)). That is why often that bishop immediately moves again to b3. In many lines, Black gets the bishop pair advantage in a semi-open position after Nb8-c6-a5-b3 or Nb8-d7-c5-b3.

If we develop the bishop to d3 then our knight on d4 becomes undefended. Black will often play Nb8-c6 to exploit this, and if we meet it with Nxc6, then after ...bxc6 Black will have a stronger potential in the center (like in the McDonnell-De Labourdonnais game). If we defend our knight with Bc1-e3 then the Nf6-g4 jump becomes the problem. White is sometimes aiming for the fianchetto (g3+Bg2) but the problem is that it takes one tempo longer...

These were the main reasons why I landed on the Bf1-e2 setup. Sure, that is not an active square for our bishop, but at least this way we castle quickly without being worried about our unprotected pieces. The bishop also covers the g4-square in case of Nf6-g4, for example. The other minor pieces go to natural squares (Nc3 and Be3(or Bg5)). In most cases, we cannot go Bf4 because of the pawn fork on e5.

Other problems for White in the Sicilian are that Black could bother our pieces. For example, ...Nf6 and ...Bb4 would bother our pawn on e4, a6+b5+b4 would bother our knight on c3 and indirectly the pawn on e4 (Black's knight is in 90%+ of cases on f6), e7-e5 kicks our knight away, ...Nc6 and ...Qb6 would bother our d4-knight and the b2-pawn... } 
2. Nf3 { Our general setup will be d4+Nxd4+Nc3+Be2+O-O+Be3(g5). Useful moves: a4 (preventing b5), f4 (taking more central space), Qd2, Rfd1. If Black goes e7-e5 we try to let the knight go b5-d6 or f5-d6. If that is not an option then we retreat to f3. Also, we will be aiming to put the c-pawn on c4 if possible. This would give us more space and significantly decrease Black's potential in the center and on the queenside. } Nc6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 e5 
5. Nb5! } { The knight is coming to d6. This will create major obstacles to the development of Black's pieces. Do not go to b5 when Black's pawn is already on d6! You will just get kicked away with a7-a6! } a6 
6. Nd6+! } Bxd6 
7. Qxd6 { White gets a bishop pair advantage. Also, Black cannot complete their development. The only thing for Black to do is offer the queen trade with ...Qe7 or ...Qf6. } Qe7 
8. Qxe7+ { This capture is the simplest. Without the queens, White does not have to worry about the king's safety anymore. } ( 8.Qd1+ { is the strongest and most played move. Black is significantly ahead in development, however, White has long-term advantages. White has a two-bishop advantage and a better pawn structure (the backward d-pawn and the weak d5-square). } ) Ngxe7 
9. c4 } { White does not have a natural way to handle the ...Nc2+ threat. We should either put the knight on the rim (the a3-square) or move our king. } 
10. Kd1 $14  } { Black cannot stop the following moves: Nc3, Be3, f3 (if necessary to support the center), Be2, and Kd2 connecting the rooks. } ( { After } 10.Na3 !? { , we would have difficulties developing the a1-rook because of the hanging a2-pawn. Stockfish still goes Be3 and O-O-O because then the d6-pawn would be hanging. } ) *

