Other problems for White in the Sicilian are that Black could bother our pieces. For example, ...Nf6 and ...Bb4 would bother our pawn on e4, a6+b5+b4 would bother our knight on c3 and indirectly the pawn on e4 (Black's knight is in 90%+ of cases on f6), e7-e5 kicks our knight away, ...Nc6 and ...Qb6 would bother our d4-knight and the b2-pawn... } 
2. Nf3 { Our general setup will be d4+Nxd4+Nc3+Be2+O-O+Be3(g5). Useful moves: a4 (preventing b5), f4 (taking more central space), Qd2, Rfd1. If Black goes e7-e5 we try to let the knight go b5-d6 or f5-d6. If that is not an option then we retreat to f3. Also, we will be aiming to put the c-pawn on c4 if possible. This would give us more space and significantly decrease Black's potential in the center and on the queenside. } Nc6 
3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 e5 
5. Nb5! } { The knight is coming to d6. This will create major obstacles to the development of Black's pieces. Do not go to b5 when Black's pawn is already on d6! You will just get kicked away with a7-a6! } d6 
6. c4!? } } { With this move White wins the fight for the center. The development is easy, natural, and unstoppable. The bishops go to e2 and e3, the knight goes to c3, and the other one will retreat to a3 and then could go to c2. We castle the king, put the queen to d2 and the rooks to c1 and d1. Easy and natural! } { Sometimes Black is trying for a quick f7-f5 pawn break. } Be7 
7. N1c3!? a6 
8. Na3 f5 
9. exf5 Bxf5 { Now, we can develop our bishop to a more active square. } 
10. Bd3!? } Be6 { Black loses a tempo, so we can do the same. } 
11. Nc2!? ( { There is nothing wrong with castling first, and then taking care of the knight on a3: } 11.O-O !? Nf6 12.Nc2 { and now } 12...O-O 13.Ne3 { transposes to our mainline. However, Black does get an extra option in @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/1p2b1pp/p1npbn2/4p3/2P5/2NB4/PPN2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 5 12@@EndFEN@@ 12...d5!? } ) Nf6 
12. Ne3 } { We are taking firm control over the d5-square. } O-O 
13. O-O } { Our next moves would be b3+Bb2(maybe a3)+Qd2 connecting the rooks. } Qd7 
14. b3 Rac8 
15. Bb2 $14  } { The knights are ready to jump to the weak squares. } *

