Our set-up is Rf1-e1, Be2-f1 (we need to defend the e4-pawn and X-Ray the e5-pawn with our rook). And then we are going to put the knight on d5. The mainlines in this pawn structure revolve around the d5-square. } ( 8.Nd2?! { Here, this idea is not as good as in the Najdorf since Black has developed the knight to c6 and did not weaken the b6-square. } 8...Be6!? { 8...d5!? 9.Nxd5 Nxd5 10.exd5 Qxd5 11.O-O Be7 12.Nc4 Be6!? $13 Unlike in the Najdorf variation, the square on b6 is not weak! } 9.Nc4?! d5! 10.exd5 Nxd5 11.Nxd5 Qxd5 12.Qxd5 Bxd5 $15 { In the Najdorf variation, the pawn on e5 was hanging and the b6-square was available to us. In this line, Black is just better due to good control of the center. } ) Be7 ( { After } 8...Be6 { we also play } 9.Re1 { , which indirectly prevents the d6-d5 breakthrough: } 9...d5? 10.exd5! Nxd5 11.Nxd5! Qxd5 12.Qxd5! Bxd5 13.Nxe5! Nxe5 14.Bb5++- { , winning a pawn. } ) 
