Other problems for White in the Sicilian are that Black could bother our pieces. For example, ...Nf6 and ...Bb4 would bother our pawn on e4, a6+b5+b4 would bother our knight on c3 and indirectly the pawn on e4 (Black's knight is in 90%+ of cases on f6), e7-e5 kicks our knight away, ...Nc6 and ...Qb6 would bother our d4-knight and the b2-pawn... } 
2. Nf3 { Our general setup will be d4+Nxd4+Nc3+Be2+O-O+Be3(g5). Useful moves: a4 (preventing b5), f4 (taking more central space), Qd2, Rfd1. If Black goes e7-e5 we try to let the knight go b5-d6 or f5-d6. If that is not an option then we retreat to f3. Also, we will be aiming to put the c-pawn on c4 if possible. This would give us more space and significantly decrease Black's potential in the center and on the queenside. } d6 
3. d4 cxd4 ( 3...Nf6 4.Nc3 cxd4 5.Nxd4 { transposes to the mainline. } ) 
4. Nxd4 } 
5. Nc3 ( { Almost any other move would be met with } 5.c4! ) a6 { With this move Black is preparing e7-e5. This is a fascinating position. Do you know how many decent moves there are for White here? I know at least 19(!) decent moves in this position! It's an unbelievably rich position for both sides! } 
6. Be2!? e5 } { The point of Black's previous move was to prevent the Bb5+ check. } 
7. Nf3!? } { This move is understandable. The knight is still attacking the center and is ready to jump to g5, for example, when the bishop appears on e6. We plan to fight for the d5 square with 8.Bg5. } ( { By far the main move is } 7.Nb3!? { The thing is that I find it difficult to explain what the knight is doing on b3. That is why I decided to stick with 7.Nf3. } ) h6 { This tricky move prevents our idea. Black is fighting for the d5-square. The beauty of the Najdorf variation for Black is that often when White plays logical moves, Black gets an advantage! For example, here it appears that the best play for White involves moving the knight to d2. If White continues to play normal logical moves then Black would play Be6+Be7+O-O and then break through with d6-d5 at some point. } 
8. Nd2!? { The strongest players choose this move right now. The idea is to transfer the knight to e3 as quickly as possible. This would effectively eliminate the strategic d6-d5 breakthrough. This goes against the principles; however, since Black lost time with moves like ...a6 and ...h6 White can afford this. } ( { There are other reasonable alternatives lines like } 8.O-O { , } ) ( 8.Be3 { , or } ) ( 8.a4 { . } ) Be6 
9. Nc4 } } b5 ( 9...Be7 10.Be3! { $14 The knight is coming to b6. That would be extremely uncomfortable for Black. It is worth pointing out that Nbd7 does not work because of the hanging pawn on d6. } ) 
10. Ne3 } { The knight is blocking the bishop on c1. So we cannot let that stay the way it is. Our next moves would be 0-0 and a2-a4. } Nbd7 
