I must admit that 1...c5 was the most challenging move to face when the goal was to follow the principles laid out before. With any other move besides 1...e5 or 1...c5, White can quickly put another pawn on d4. After that, White's development is easy and natural, as White has many options when two pawns are in the center.

With 1...e5, White develops the knight to f3 with a tempo. In the case of 2...Nc6 the bishop goes to c4 easily. After 1...c5, however, simply going for Nf3 and Bc4 is somewhat dangerous. Black has an option of playing a6+b5 or e7-e6, followed by d7-d5! Generally speaking, we cannot stop the latter.

That is why I decided to go for the main line 3. d4. After the knight reaches d4, White's development should be easy. Then I was thinking about the f1-bishop. If we put it on c4 then it becomes extremely vulnerable to various attacks (a6+b5, e6+d5, Qd8-c7, Nb8-c6-e5(a5)). That is why often that bishop immediately moves again to b3. In many lines, Black gets the bishop pair advantage in a semi-open position after Nb8-c6-a5-b3 or Nb8-d7-c5-b3.

If we develop the bishop to d3 then our knight on d4 becomes undefended. Black will often play Nb8-c6 to exploit this, and if we meet it with Nxc6, then after ...bxc6 Black will have a stronger potential in the center (like in the McDonnell-De Labourdonnais game). If we defend our knight with Bc1-e3 then the Nf6-g4 jump becomes the problem. White is sometimes aiming for the fianchetto (g3+Bg2) but the problem is that it takes one tempo longer...

These were the main reasons why I landed on the Bf1-e2 setup. Sure, that is not an active square for our bishop, but at least this way we castle quickly without being worried about our unprotected pieces. The bishop also covers the g4-square in case of Nf6-g4, for example. The other minor pieces go to natural squares (Nc3 and Be3(or Bg5)). In most cases, we cannot go Bf4 because of the pawn fork on e5.

Other problems for White in the Sicilian are that Black could bother our pieces. For example, ...Nf6 and ...Bb4 would bother our pawn on e4, a6+b5+b4 would bother our knight on c3 and indirectly the pawn on e4 (Black's knight is in 90%+ of cases on f6), e7-e5 kicks our knight away, ...Nc6 and ...Qb6 would bother our d4-knight and the b2-pawn... } 
2. Nf3 { Our general setup will be d4+Nxd4+Nc3+Be2+O-O+Be3(g5). Useful moves: a4 (preventing b5), f4 (taking more central space), Qd2, Rfd1. If Black goes e7-e5 we try to let the knight go b5-d6 or f5-d6. If that is not an option then we retreat to f3. Also, we will be aiming to put the c-pawn on c4 if possible. This would give us more space and significantly decrease Black's potential in the center and on the queenside. } a6 
3. c4! } } { We are going to use the momentum to put the pawn to c4! You should try doing that when you get a chance. Our plan is d4+Nxd4+Nc3+Be2+O-O+Be3+Qd2, connecting the rooks. } ( { The idea of Black's tricky move is revealed in the following line: } 3.d4?! cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nf6 5.Nc3 { 5.e5?? Qa5+ $17 This typical trick wins the e5-pawn with a check. } 5...e5! { and there is no Ndb5. The knight has to come back. The bishop from f8 is not blocked by the d6-pawn, so it easily gets out. } 6.Nf5? d5! { $15 Black gets the center due the bishop's attack on the knight on f5. } ) Nc6 ( 3...Nf6 4.Nc3 Nc6 5.d4 cxd4 6.Nxd4 { transposes to 5...Nf6 followed by 6...e5, which we will see shortly. } ) 
4. d4! cxd4 
5. Nxd4 Nf6 
6. Nc3 e5 
7. Nf5 d5 
8. cxd5 Nxe4 { White has several options. None of them lead to a simple position, unless you are willing to be worse out of the opening. } ( { Meanwhile, } 8...Bxf5 9.exf5 Nd4 { transposes to the mainline of this variation. } ) 
9. dxc6 { This straightforward line simplifies the position. } ( { After } 9.Ne3!? Nxc3 10.bxc3 Na4!? { $14 Black has the potential to attack on the kingside. } ) ( 9.Ng3 { also leads to some kingside potential for Black after } 9...Nxc3!? 10.bxc3 Na5 { . The computer says that White is better. However, it is easier to play for Black, I think. } ) ( 9.Nxg7+!? { wins a pawn. } 9...Bxg7 10.Nxe4 Nd4 11.Nc3 O-O 12.Bd3 f5 { Black gets a strong center in exchange for the missing pawn. Here are some sample lines: } 13.Be3 { leads to crazy complications. } { 13.O-O f4 leads to an attack for Black. } 13...f4 14.Bxd4 exd4 15.Qh5 { 15.Ne4 f3! } 15...h6 16.Ne4 Qa5+ 17.Kd1 $14 { The engine likes White's position. The king on d1 is apparently safe... } ) Qxd1+□ 
10. Nxd1! { We do not want to lose the right to castle. } Bb4+ 
11. Nc3 Nxc3?? 
12. a3! } { That is a typical punch. The idea is that if the bishop moves to a5 then White will have b2-b4 with a tempo. } Ba5?? 
13. cxb7! Bxb7 ( 13...Ne4+ 14.b4! { +- shows the point of including the move a2-a3. } ) 
14. Nd6++- } { Wins the bishop. } *

