5. Nc3 } { Black is playing very aggressive chess. We cannot just play calm chess anymore. You need to memorize the following moves. They all are sensible and understandable. } ( 5...Nc6 6.Ndb5 { transposes to other lines. } ) ( 5...d6 6.Be2 { transposes to 5...e6. } ) 
6. e5! } Ne4 { This line also leads to a winning advantage for White. However, White needs to play very precisely. } 
7. Qg4! } { The pawn on g7 is a typical target when the f8-bishop leaves. } Nxc3 
8. Qxg7! } { For now, White is one piece down and Black has a discovered check. } Rf8 ( 8...Nd5+ 9.c3+- { White wins back the piece while Black's kingside is collapsing. } ) 
9. a3! { You need to memorize this move! It is critical to force the bishop to decide on which diagonal it wants to stay. If it stays on a3/f8 then we win the knight. If not, then the f8-rook would be in trouble. } Ba5 } { The bishop leaves the rook on f8... } ( { After } 9...Be7 10.bxc3+- { White wins a pawn. Also, Black's kingside is in big trouble. } ) 
10. Bh6! } { Developing the bishop with a mate in one threat. } Qe7 ( 10...Nd5+ 11.b4!? { +- wins a lot of material. } ) 
11. Nb3! } { That is another move that you need to remember. It breaks the fragile balance between the bishop and the knight. } Bc7 
12. bxc3+- { White can win the exchange on f8 at any moment. Useful moves are: f2-f4 securing the crucial e5-pawn, develop the bishop and castle kingside. } *

