3. d4 cxd4 
4. Nxd4 } a6 
5. c4!? } } { Since Black is not threatening anything, we are putting another pawn in the center. } Nf6 
6. Nc3 ( 6.e5? Qa5+! 7.Nc3 Qxe5 $15 { wins a pawn with a check. } ) Qc7 
7. a3!? } { The simplest. Otherwise, we would have to worry about the pin. Black wasted a tempo with a6 so we can do the same. The set-up is Be2+O-O+Be3+Rc1+Qd2+Rfd1. If Black attacks our e4-pawn with the bishop on b7 then we play f2-f3. } ( { An alternative you could look into is } 7.Be2!? Bb4 8.Nc2!? Bxc3+ 9.bxc3 d6 { You have to be ready to lose the pawn: 9...Nxe4? 10.Qd4! Nf6 11.Bf4! Qd8 12.Bd6! $16 and Black will not castle anytime soon. } 10.Ba3!? Nxe4 11.Qd4! f5 12.Bh5+! Kf8 { with weird complications, e.g. } 13.Rd1!? Nc6 14.Qe3 { . } ) Nc6 
8. Be2 } Bc5 
9. Be3 $14  } { Securing the knight. Castling and Qd2 are unstoppable. } *

