1. e4 Nf6 { Alekhine's Defense. } 
2. e5! } } { We are using the central pawn to kick the knight away from a great square. } Nd5 
3. d4 { Another pawn goes to the center. } d6 
{ The easiest way to play here is the following one: } 4. c4 { Another pawn in the center with a tempo! } ( 4.Nf3!? { is a more popular line. I did not choose this one because Black already has several reasonable responses: } 4...dxe5 { , } { 4...g6 , 4...Bg4 and 4...Nc6 . Also, it is quite logical to move the pawn to c4 with a tempo. } ) Nb6 
5. exd6!? { This move clarifies the situation in the center. We do not have to worry about the possible capture on e5 anymore. Our powerful pawn on e5 has already accomplished the goal of kicking Black's knight off the f6-square. So now it can have some rest. } ( 5.f4! { is objectively the strongest line for White, as you can learn from any chess engine. The problem for us is that White gets behind in development and moreover, these pawn advances leave our king vulnerable. } ) exd6 { In this line, White will easily complete the development with Nf3+Be2+O-O+Nc3+Re1, etc. } 
6. Nf3 Be7 
7. Be2 { Development. } O-O 
