4. Nxe5 { I have an interesting story about this position to share with you. The year was 1994. Viswanathan Anand (2720) played a knockout rapid match against Ilia Smirin (2625). It was the PCA/Intel-GP rapid. The first two games ended in a draw so it was time for Armageddon. Smirin had six minutes and White pieces, and Anand had five minutes and Black pieces. You can find the video with the whole game on Youtube. In this very position, Anand spent 1:43 min on a single move! }d6 ( { I have a theory on what Vishy was thinking about. He knew that } 4...d6 { should transpose to the main line. When I was watching the video I realized what variation would come across my mind. What if White captures on f7 after } ) ( 4...d6? ) 
5. Nxf7?? { I think this was the move that Anand was afraid of! He did not have to go 4...d6 because 4...d5 was a perfectly playable alternative. I think it took him more than 100 seconds out of his overall 300 to land on 4...d6 and see the refutation to 5.Nxf7?? } ( { Meanwhile, } 5.Nf3 { would transpose to the mainline of 3.Nxe5. } ) Qe7! } { This is the move! Black is delaying the capture! There is a bigger threat now! } ( { The automatic recapture } 5...Kxf7?? { leads to a big advantage for White: } 6.Qh5+! g6 { 6...Ke7 7.Qe2! d5 8.Bg5+! +- wins the queen. Here 8.f3!? +-, winning the knight, is good enough as well. } 7.Qd5+! Kg7 8.Qxe4! { $16 with a healthy extra pawn for White. } ) 
6. Nxh8 ( 6.Qe2 Kxf7! { +- with an extra knight for Black. } ) Nc3+! } { Discovered check! } 
7. Be3 Nxd1-+ { The game is over for White! } 
