3. Nc3 } Nf6 
4. cxd5 exd5 } { In this pawn structure which is called the Carlsbad structure, it is much harder for Black to follow the principles I've outlined earlier. This is because the logical move c7-c5 often leads to a loss of the d5-pawn. That is why the main setup for Black consists of the following moves: Be7+O-O+Nbd7+c6+Re8. Then Black tries to make space to develop the c8-bishop by moving the knight to f8. } ( 4...Nxd5 { is another option, which however loses control over the center after } 5.e4 Nxc3 6.bxc3 $14 { . Of course, this is a playable line. Many strong grandmasters have played it (and continue to play it). However, in my opinion, this line is much more difficult for Black to understand how to play. } ) 
5. Bg5 Be7 
6. e3 O-O 
7. Bd3 Nbd7 ( 7...c5?! { Here is an approximate reason why this logical move is not the best. Black gets in trouble after the following logical continuation: } 8.dxc5 Bxc5?! 9.Nge2!? Nc6 10.Nf4 { and the pawn on d5 is in big trouble. } 10...d4 { 10...Be6 11.O-O Re8? 12.Ncxd5! Bxd5 13.Nxd5! Qxd5 14.Bxf6! gxf6?? 15.Bxh7+ wins the queen: 15...Kxh7 16.Qxd5+- } 11.Bxf6! Qxf6 12.Qh5! { Mate in one is suddenly coming. } 12...g6 13.Qxc5 dxc3 14.Qxc3 Qxc3+ 15.bxc3 $16 { With a healthy extra pawn for White. } ) ( { Another line Black should avoid is } 7...b6? 8.Bxf6! Bxf6 9.Qh5! g6 10.Qxd5 $16 { and White has won a pawn. } ) 
8. Nge2 { Black's setup does not change after this move. } c6 
9. O-O ( { If White goes for queenside castling, we should launch our queenside pawns: } 9.Qc2 Re8 10.O-O-O b5! 11.Kb1 a5 $13 { and White's position is becoming dangerous. } ) Re8 
10. Qc2 Nf8 $14  } { Black has several ideas now:

1. Exchange the dark-squared bishops with Nf6-h5(g4). After that, development will become easier.

2. Develop the bishop to g4(e6 or d7).

3. Play g7-g6 followed by Nf8-e6, kicking the g5-bishop away. } 
